<note id="fs-idm179259632" class="os-teacher">
<title>Standards</title>
<para id="fs-idm266049568"><emphasis effect="bold">Topics</emphasis>: 4.3 Politics and Regional Interests, 4.11 An Age of Reform, 4.13 The Society of the South in the Early Republic</para>
<para id="fs-idm239474832"><emphasis effect="bold">Themes</emphasis>: GEO Geography and the Environment, PCE Politics and Power, ARC American and Regional Culture</para>
<para id="fs-idm253907440"><emphasis effect="bold">Learning Objectives</emphasis>: Unit 4C Explain how different regional interests affected debates about the role of the federal government in the early republic, Unit 4K Explain how and why various reform movements developed and expanded from 1800 to 1848, Unit 4M Explain how geographic and environmental factors shaped the development of the South from 1800 to 1848</para>
<para id="fs-idm243489568"><emphasis effect="bold">Historical Developments</emphasis>: 4.1.I.D, 4.3.II.B.i, 4.3.II.B.ii</para>
<para id="fs-idm262032912"><emphasis effect="bold">Historical Reasoning Skills</emphasis>: HTS-1 Developments and Processes, HTS-2 Sourcing and Situation, HTS-3 Source Claims and Evidence, HTS-4 Contextualization, HTS-5 Making Connections, HTS-6 Argumentation</para>
<para id="fs-idm260634832"><emphasis effect="bold">Reasoning Processes</emphasis>: RP-1 Comparison, RP-2 Causation, RP-3 Continuity and Change</para>
</note>
<section id="fs-idm499955040">
<para id="fs-idm226892128"><emphasis effect="bold">Lesson Objectives:</emphasis></para>
<list id="fs-idm247770640" list-type="bulleted">
<item>Students will be able to identify how attitudes toward African slavery in the United States have changed from the Founding Era to the mid-nineteenth century by a comparison reading of Thomas Jefferson‚Äôs Query XVIII from <emphasis effect="italics">Notes on the State of Virginia</emphasis> (1781), Jefferson‚Äôs letter to Bishop Henri Gr√©goire (1809), David Walker‚Äôs <emphasis effect="italics">An Appeal to the Coloured Citizens of the World</emphasis> (1829), Sarah Moore Grimk√©‚Äôs ‚ÄúAn Epistle to the Clergy of the Southern States‚Äù (1836), and William Harper‚Äôs essay ‚ÄúSlavery in Light of Social Ethics‚Äù (1837).</item>
<item>Students will analyze primary source documents by answering comprehension questions to guide them to conclusions about the arguments being presented within them.</item>
<item>Students will practice writing a thesis statement for a CCOT essay.</item>
</list>
